Housing Market Wellness Index Creation

Team 12 Capstone

Data sources

  • Use Redfin neighborhood / zip code data by month join, ratio with next
  • Redfin Boston, MA metro area level with duration of 1 week

Steps to clean housing data before integration and calculation:

  1. find zip code-city list
  2. merge on zip code granular data
  3. separate date column into day, month, year
  4. join the weekly city data with the zip code level data on the month, year column to align local level with monthly data
  5. For each zip, month find average ratio for each metric of zip:city/county
  6. Evaluate mean, st. dev., variance of ratios for each level to see if relatively uniform Hyp test:
  1. if the ratios are uniform across features, average them to find a ratio for each zip to the respective city by month
  2. if they vary a non-significant amount, choose the features that will be used in the wellness index
    1. average the ratio across each month?
    2. is there weekly seasonality for each zip code? incorporate this factor?
  1. create dataframe w/ columns: month, year, zip code, ratio or ratio per feature that can be used to readjust new data as it comes in
  2. write in function form so that this function can be used any time we want to upload new images

define function for computing ratios inputs are the column names for the 1 week and 4 week data frame

Set up 1 month (4 week) data so that it only takes the data ending with the last week of the month

This will be used for the calculation-driven join later so that the period_end roughly matches up with the end of a month date. We will accomplish this by approximating the period_end nearest to the end of the month as the closest date. Then, by setting that equal to the last day of the month, we can join in Redfin data at the appropriate frequency.

To accomplish this, we will create a new data set for the end of the month data.

  1. We will create a list of the end dates for each month in the dates following 2020-01-01
  2. We will convert all dates to their respective integers for distance calculations
  1. integers start from 1/1/1970 (default)
  1. For each end of month date, we will find the closest row in the redfin_weekly_1month_MA df from the period_end date
  2. The new, desired dataframe will have the rows categorized as closest to the end of the month and that end-of-month date
  3. We will later join on that end date to ensure times match up.

The data is stored in a table: mod_monthends_rf (modified month ends redfin)

# 1. Create a list of the end dates of each month
# find the end dates for each month in the dataset using lubridate, then grab the unique values
end_month_dates <- data.frame(month_end = unique(ceiling_date(redfin_weekly_1month_MA$period_begin, unit= "month") - 1))

# 2. We will convert all dates to their respective integers for distance calculations
# int_end_month_dates <- as.integer(end_month_dates)
ind_period_end_dates <- data.frame(index = c(1:nrow(redfin_weekly_1month_MA)),
                                   date = redfin_weekly_1month_MA$period_end,
                                   county = redfin_weekly_1month_MA$county
                                   )

# 3. Find the closest date to each end date, list index -- for each county
days_dist <- vector()

# unique list of counties
counties_uniq <- unique(redfin_weekly_1month_MA$county)

for (ch_county in counties_uniq) {
  county_rows <- filter(ind_period_end_dates, county == ch_county)
    for (i in 1:nrow(end_month_dates)) {
      for (j in 1:nrow(ind_period_end_dates)) {
        days_dist[j] <- abs(as.integer(end_month_dates[i,1] - county_rows$date[j]))
        closest_day <- order(days_dist)[1]
        end_month_dates$nearest_index[i] <- county_rows$index[closest_day]
    }
    }
  end_month_dates[,ch_county] <- end_month_dates$nearest_index
}

# drop nearest_index column and melt county columns into data frame
end_month_dates <- end_month_dates[, -which(names(end_month_dates) == "nearest_index")]
week4_month_indexes <- melt(end_month_dates, id = "month_end")

# order on county, date
week4_month_indexes <- week4_month_indexes[order(week4_month_indexes$variable, week4_month_indexes$month_end),]


# 4. Create desired dataframe with chosen index values and add target_date column for selected date
mod_monthends_rf <- redfin_weekly_1month_MA[week4_month_indexes$value, ]
mod_monthends_rf <- cbind(target_date = week4_month_indexes$month_end, mod_monthends_rf)

Create a function that calculates the ratio for each metric of zip code: county, by month, for all rows after 2019

# function takes the names of the desired columns for each dataset
# col1 ~ red_wcounty metric
# col2 ~ mod_monthends_rf
ratio_calc_weekly <- function(col1, col2) {
  # column column names of choice for data1 (zillred_wcounty)
  cols_data1 <- c("county","state","date", "Region", "primary_city", col1)
  data1 <- red_wcounty[,cols_data1]
  data1$CountyName <- factor(data1$county)
  
  # column column names of choice for data2 mod_monthends_rf
  cols_data2 <- c("county", "state", "target_date", col2)
  data2 <- mod_monthends_rf[,cols_data2]
  data2$county <- factor(data2$county)
  
  # join the columns on county, date
  joined_zip_county <- inner_join(data1, data2,
             by = c("CountyName" = "county", 
                    "date" = "target_date"))
  
  # calculate the ratio between the two columns
  joined_zip_county$ratio <- joined_zip_county[,col1] / joined_zip_county[,col2]
  return(joined_zip_county)
}

# for zillred_wcounty

                  'median_sale_price_yoy',
                  'total_homes_sold',
                  'total_new_listings',
                  'inventory',
                  'median_days_on_market',
                  'average_sale_to_list_ratio'
)

metric_comps <- rbind(metric_names_zip, metric_names_county)

Loop through the comparative metrics to create a dataframe of the ratios by city

# initialize empty dataframe for storing the ratios for each metric
rows_for_empty <- nrow(inner_join(red_wcounty[,c("county","state","date", "Region", "primary_city")],
                mod_monthends_rf[,c("county", "state", "target_date")],
             by = c("county" = "county", 
                    "date" = "target_date")))
df_ratios <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(metric_names_county), nrow = rows_for_empty))
colnames(df_ratios) <- metric_names_county

# loop through the metrics and add the ratios for each to their respective columns
for (i in 1:ncol(metric_comps)) {
  # calculate ratio using respective measures
  exec_ratio_func <- ratio_calc_weekly(metric_comps[1,i], metric_comps[2,i])

  # store variables in appropriate columns
  df_ratios[,c(metric_comps[2,i])] <- exec_ratio_func$ratio
}

df_ratios[,c("date")] <- exec_ratio_func$date
df_ratios[,c("county")] <- exec_ratio_func$CountyName
df_ratios[,c("primary_city")] <- exec_ratio_func$primary_city
df_ratios[,c("zip_code")] <- exec_ratio_func$Region

# get rid of missing rows
df_ratios <- df_ratios[complete.cases(df_ratios),]

Join the ratios with the weekly, county data

  • Then, multiply the ratios by the county numbers to get the town level numbers
# merge ratios for each zip on the county, state, month of weekly's period end date

# create a month and year column for each df
df_ratios$month <- month(df_ratios$date)
df_ratios$year <- year(df_ratios$date)
redfin_byweek_MA$month <- month(redfin_byweek_MA$period_end)
redfin_byweek_MA$year <- year(redfin_byweek_MA$period_end)

# columns with ".x" are from ratio df, columns with ".y" are the by-county values
ratios_values_merged <- merge(x = df_ratios
      , y = redfin_byweek_MA[, c("county", "state", "month", "year","period_end", metric_names_county)]
      , by.x = c("county", "month", "year")
      , by.y = c("county", "month", "year"))


# order ratios_values_merged by primary_city, county, date
ratios_values_merged <- arrange(ratios_values_merged, primary_city, county, period_end)
ratios_values_merged <- ratios_values_merged[complete.cases(ratios_values_merged),]

# multiply the ratios X respective metrics
colnames.x <- paste(metric_names_county, ".x", sep = "")
colnames.y <- paste(metric_names_county, ".y", sep = "")

applied_ratios <- ratios_values_merged[, colnames.x] * ratios_values_merged[, colnames.y]
applied_ratios$average_sale_to_list_ratio <- applied_ratios$average_sale_to_list_ratio - 1


# output_data_county
output_data_county <- cbind(ratios_values_merged[, c("zip_code", 
                                                "primary_city", "county", 
                                                "state", "period_end")],
                       applied_ratios)
